        <li id="en13">An individual in the Department of Human Services in one of the counties in Western PA recently made a post on solving homelessness: &ldquo;&hellip;your authority and your funding sit in only one system&hellip;You design good programs&hellip;you ask for better outcomes&hellip;the same people keep showing up in different places&hellip;Hospitals. Shelters. Jails&hellip;because the systems aren&rsquo;t aligned&hellip;The most effective solutions&hellip;start with two systems staying in their lane, but coordinating earlier.&rdquo; A person inside the system diagnosing the problematic&mdash;impressive in itself. However, the proposed solution shifts the crossing earlier in the process, which, as this essay argues, is no solution at all.</li>
        <li id="en14"><a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-026-00369-3" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Shumailov et al., Nature (2024). See also Appendix A.</a></li>
        <li id="en15">The structure of Path 3 resonates with Deleuze and Guattari&rsquo;s distinction in <em>A Thousand Plateaus</em> (1980) between arborescent and rhizomatic organization. The masquerading institution is arborescent: a single root logic ([ECO] rationality), a trunk (infrastructure), branches (programs, metrics, campaigns). The parallel channels&mdash;informal mutual aid, proximity networks, weak-tie giving&mdash;are rhizomatic: no root logic, no trunk, multiple entry and exit points, propagating horizontally through unexpected connections. The counsel is not simply &ldquo;preserve parallel infrastructure&rdquo;; it is more active: rhizomatic [CHA] does not need to defeat the arborescent system; it needs to remain heterogeneous to it. The danger is not capture by force; it is voluntary entry into the root logic. Every time informal giving adopts EA&rsquo;s language of impact and efficiency to justify itself, it plugs into the tree. The rhizome survives by refusing that translation. GoFundMe is arguably a re-territorialization of the rhizomatic impulse to share resources informally through weak-tie networks: the platform took the rhizome and gave it a root.</li>
